article.headline: Reserve scores all 15 points in second half
article.linkText: Liberty stay perfect at home with win over Fever
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- When the Indiana Fever just could not score, the New York Liberty's Elena Baranova just could not miss. Crystal Robinson scored 18 points, and Baranova had all 15 of hers in the second half, leading the New York Liberty past the Indiana Fever 73-65 Sunday. Robinson hit a 3-pointer to start New York's second-half push, and Baranova scored 10 points in a three-minute stretch as the Liberty (9-8) finished off the Fever with tough defense. "I was wide open -- a couple of shots, there was nobody around me," Baranova said. "Maybe they thought I couldn't make it. It wasn't me -- it was them." Baranova was 6-of-7 from the field. "That's one of the things I love about this team: We're not a one-, two- or three-superstar team," said Weatherspoon, who had a season-high 13 points plus five assists. "It's all of us." Rookie Coretta Brown scored 13 for Indiana (10-9), which went on a scoreless drought of nearly 6 minutes in the second half, allowing the Liberty to build a double-digit lead. Tamika Catchings and Kristen Rasmussen each scored 12 for the Fever, now 0-5 at Madison Square Garden. Indiana is 2-8 on the road this season. "We have to start winning games on the road," Catchings said. "We didn't step up and stop anybody." Robinson's 3-pointer with 10:26 left tied the game at 46 after Indiana had built an 11-point lead. Baranova then took over, shaking two defenders for a jumper that gave the Liberty the lead, hitting two 3s and driving for a layup during a 23-4 run. "We played that momentum to the end," Robinson said. "We always have that kind of run in us. We just need to come out like that from the beginning." Indiana, the WNBA's top 3-point shooting team, made a late comeback behind 3s from Brown, Catchings and Nikki McCray. But eventually the Fever were forced to foul the Liberty, who hit 13 free throws in the final 3:36. "They hit big shots, uncontested shots. We just didn't make defensive stops," Indiana coach Nell Fortner said. "They made us pay for our mistakes." After a sloppy start, the Fever went on a 10-0 run to go up 24-17 in the first half, but Robinson and Vickie Johnson hit 3-pointers to spark a 10-2 run that gave New York a 27-26 lead. Brown then made a pair of jumpers, including one at the buzzer, to put Indiana up 30-27 at halftime.

Game notes
Indiana's starting point guard, Niele Ivey, did not play after breaking a bone in her right hand Wednesday against Detroit. She's expected to be out two weeks. Sonja Henning started in her place. ... Tari Phillips added nine points and 10 rebounds for the Liberty, and Johnson had 10 points.
